\begin{MintedVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
History mechanism

\PYG{k}{1.} In the early 1990s, the market for a Standard Industrial Raw Material faced a severe primary production deficit as strategic inventories were depleted faster than new extraction operations could be commissioned. Primary global production remained consistently below annual industrial requirements, forcing the sector to rely on finite discretionary inventories that eventually reached critical lows.
\PYG{k}{2.} The exhaustion of these stockpiles triggered a phase of panic\PYGZhy{}buying by industrial utilities, creating a speculative environment where buyers competed for limited uncommitted supply.
\PYG{k}{3.} This led to a realized speculative price bubble peaking at approximately \PYGZdl{}120/lb in late 1995.
\PYG{k}{4.} The peak was broken when a large\PYGZhy{}scale conversion program, launched in 1993, began successfully repurposing decommissioned materials into commercial fuel from around 1995, flooding the market with secondary supply.
\PYG{k}{5.} Followed by a rapid market correction back toward \PYGZdl{}30/lb by March, 1998.

Forecast mechanism

\PYG{k}{1.} The Standard Industrial Raw Material sector in late 1998 entered a phase of severe supply\PYGZhy{}side rationalization, as market prices dropped below the marginal cost of production for global Tier\PYGZhy{}1 extraction assets.
\PYG{k}{2.} Persistent low prices are expected to force major operators to suspend high\PYGZhy{}cost production facilities, significantly tightening the available primary supply in the global market.
\PYG{k}{3.} A freeze in exploration capital expenditure during the market slump is projected to prevent the development of a new project pipeline; these extraction sites typically require 7\PYGZhy{}10 years from discovery to first production due to the complexity of regulatory licensing, geological confirmation drilling, and facility construction, meaning that even a future price recovery cannot quickly unlock new supply to meet growing industrial demand.
\PYG{k}{4.} As secondary supplies from conversion programs are projected to stabilize, the market is expected to recognize an impending structural deficit triggered by steady growth in reactor requirements.
\PYG{k}{5.} That tightening forward balance, built by facility suspensions and the absence of new project development, is expected to draw utilities back into aggressive long\PYGZhy{}term contracting, lifting prices sharply toward approximately \PYGZdl{}80/lb by late 2001.
\PYG{k}{6.} We anticipate a projected non\PYGZhy{}linear recovery, with prices finding a cyclical floor at \PYGZdl{}20/lb in 1999 before trending upward toward a secondary peak of approximately \PYGZdl{}80/lb by late 2001.
\end{MintedVerbatim}
